column168: The driver of the tractor-trailer found a small leak at the rear of his trailer, when he opened the trailer he found product on the trailer floor.  The drums were labeled at UN-1263, Elastospray Isocyante, a paint product.  The driver notified Covenant Transport whom contacted ACT to dispatch a response team for cleanup.  Upon arrived of the response team they identified the leaking drum and over packed it into an 85-gallon poly drum.  Granular sorbents were used to cleanup the spilled product in the trailer.  All cleanup material was placed into a 55-gallon metal drum.  All waste will be disposed to a permitted fscility.    It appears that the drum was damaged prior to transport and no load shift was apparent.

column168: A van trailer was backed into the dock at the intended waste disposal facility.  It was noticed while opening the doors that some material had leaked onto the floor of the trailer.  The emergency reponse team was notified, donned the appropriate PPE and entered the trailer.  The spill was contained and limited to the trailer floor before any of the material spilled to the ground.  The spill was contained with a suitable absorbent material which was placed into a drum and disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.  The leaking drum was placed into a suitable salvage drum and also disposed of at the same facility.  The trailer was cleaned with a cleaning compound after unloading.
column169: The origin location that loaded the trailer was informed that a sharp object protruding from the side of the trailer had caused the leak and cautioned employees to be alert to such hazards.

column168: The shipment had been unloaded from a van trailer and was on the dock at the 10 day storage facility.  An inspection noted that a small amount of material had leaked from the container.  Facility personnel donned the appropriate PPE and placed a suitable absorbent material on the spill.  It was found that the bung closure on the drum was loose, causing the material to leak.  The drum was properly closed, the absorbent material was placed into a suitable salvage container and the shipment was loaded on a trailer to the intended waste disposal facility.  Louisiana Haz Mat Division was notified.  Officer Walter Hingle, Rpt. #09-00660
column169: The drum had not been properly closed.  The shipper was notified and all personnel involved were to review proper drum closure procedures.

column168: Drain valve on overflow-shutoff tank either opened in transit or was not properly closed prior to movement. Approximately 3-4 gallons of liquid material drained into hose trough and less than that leaked over back of trough as vheicle overtook incline. Driver arlrted by local Sheriff. Driver stopped, called emergency coordinator. Emergency coordinator also notified by local EMA. EC called Hepaco (private response contractor)and authorized cleanup. Local EMA re-routed traffic arround tank-trailer and vehicle for a little over 4 hours in west bound lane. Total of cleanup material and residues including the weight of 55 gallon 1A2 container = 75 lbs.    Hose rack cleaned, liquid contained by driver added to sorbent material in drum. Spilled material cleaned from road(<1gallon). RQ=100lbs.~D001 This was not a RQ Spill.
column169: Leaking valve inspected and appears to be in proper working order. Discussed operating proceedures with driver. Driver confirms proceedures were followed. Incident will be used as a lesson in first-quarter safety meetings.

column168: A BNSF eastbound train went into emergency on single main track as it was slowing to a stop. Train inspection revealed BN 974302 (ICC 111A100W1 tank car) had derailed upright with both trucks out from under this tank car. The A-end tank head embedded into the ballast, but the tank was not compromised. The derailment cause was attributed to BN 974302's center sill that failed at an existing partial fracture (40% old break) towards the A-end of this tank car. The closed bottom outlet unloading arrangement of T-piping was damaged by ground impact and residual product that remained inside the damaged piping escaped. BNSF contract responders treated the impacted soil/ballast with a microbial bioremediation agent targeting hydrocarbons.   The side specification stencil on BN 974302 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2000 and next due in 2010.
column169: The BNSF issued a Mechanical Alert to initiate detailed inspections of center sills on the BNSF tank car fleet.

column168: El Paso driver was waiting in line for inspection at the White Sands Missile Range (New Mexico) before making his delivery.  The guard at the inspection area notice a slow leak from the underneath side of the trailer which the guard then informed the driver. After putting on his appropriate PPE, the driver safely climbed into the trailer and found that 15 gallon container of Hydrochloric Acid had formed a leak.  This was caused by a nail puncture from the pallet that the drum was sitting on during transit.  The drum was flipped over in order to apply "hardening putty" and it was then placed into an overpack drum.  The driver reported the incident to his supervisor in El Paso and to inform that he had secured the container from leaking further which he informed the guards the same.  The guards had already had already dispatched the "White Sands Missile Range" Fire Department who is stationed onsite.  It was reported to the firemen that the leaking drum was already contained which they confirmed.  The Emergency Responders (WSMR Fire Dept) were called by the guard since the incident occurred on government property.  The Emergency Responders were inpressed how the driver contained the leak and secured the area.  The neutralized area on the road was placed in a bag for Univar to dispose of the material.  The drum was weighed at the Univar facility and it was short approximately 1 pound (16 ounces).
column169: To improve or prevent similiar future incidents, all pallets will be inspected for damaged before use.  Pallets that have broken, missing, boards or pretruding nails will be discarded.  Before drums are placed on the pallets for storage or transit, slip protective cardboard sheets will be placed on each pallet to prevent damaged to the palletized containers.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading, one carton containing one, 28.12 kilogram cylinder fell over during handling.  Approximately 10 liquid kilograms of free product were released from the cylinder. The incident was the result of the carton not being properly banded to the skid, causing the carton to fall over.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel secured the leaking cylinder and the cylinder was placed into a salvage drum.  The salvage drum will be held at the terminal pending instructions from the shipper.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF roadswitch crew reported NATX 72473 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) leaking commodity from the top fitting area during normal switching activities in the railyard. NATX 72473 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected NATX 72473 and observed that the spillage had emanated from the vacuum relief valve (VRV). The product outage was checked and deemed appropriate. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Responders removed the VRV and a stainless steel pipe plug was inserted in the vacated VRV orifice to seal it. It appeared that the VRV was stuck in the open position and it expelled product during movement via a hydraulic surge within the tank car. The spillage on the tank shell was cleaned with a mixture of Micro-Blaze and water. No ground impact was evident. Clean-up was completed by 1418 hrs. CST, 2/08/09.  Intact seals removed numbered 057614 and 1052766. Seals applied were SRS 000418 at the manway and SRS 000412 at the valve housing cover.  The side specification stencil on NATX 72473 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: DOWX 70270 (AAR 211A100W1 tank car) was found with small amount of expelled product at the manway closure by a California PUC Hazardous Material Inspector during a routine inspection in the railyard. Three of the six manway securement bolts were reported in less than a tool tight condition. A BNSF mechanical responder whom was with the inspector immediately tool tightened the loose manway securement bolts. The manway gasket was not inspected, leaving the applied manway seal intact. The spillage was wiped and no ground impact was evident.  The side specification stencil on DOWX 70270 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: After taking a bottom sample the driver was directed to gear up to unload. the trailer has a rear mounted hydraulic pump. A stainless steel fitting is used to connect between the trailer external valve and the 3" pump inlet. Than product hose from the pump discharge to the customers product receiving line inlet.  the driver was ready to offload and sitting in his tractor waiting for directions from the operator. The operator asked the driver for another sample. The driver checked the external valve was shut and pulled the SS fitting from the external valve fitting and product spilled onto the containment pad. product solidified and was scraped up for disposal.  it was later discovered that the operator tried to get another sample and opened the internal and external valves in an attempt to draw material from the pump discharge. column168: The Auburn, WA terminal loaded the Dupont product to a trap trailer. The dockworker loaded 2 rolls of linoleum over top of the product. One end of the linoleum was on a load bar and the other end was placed on top of a skid of flooring. When the  trailer was moved from the dock the linoleum rolled off of the skid of flooring and struck the Dupont product causing 2 cans in separate packages to be damaged. The total release was approximately 1 liquid cup. The tops of the 2 cans were crushed as a result of the impact. The product was recouped and 5 gallons held at the carrier’s terminal. The remaining 8 gallons will be delivered February 18, 2009 as instructed by the consignee. The carrier will properly dispose of the affected 5 gallons of product. The other 3-1 gallon containers while not damaged were contaminated with paint from the release and will not be accepted by the consignee.  No exposures or injuries resulted from this incident.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 02/12/2009 at 1100hrs personnel at the CSXT Hookers Point rail yard reported an ammonia odor in the yard.  The shipper, CF Industries, and local agencies were notified and responded. CF Industries personnel inspected the tank cars in the yard to determine the source of the odor.  They identified PLMX 137630, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, as being the source of the odor.  CF Industries personnel reported the odor was possibly coming from the pressure relief device.  CF Industries using their equipment and personnel moved the tank car back to their facility (approximately one mile away) so that they could unload the car and then inspect the valve. CF Industries later advised that they were unable to confirm that there was an actual vapor release from the pressure relief device. They indicated that the residue tank car would be forwarded to a rail car repair facility to have the pressure relief device inspected and replaced if necessary.   This incident did not require a special switching move by CSXT.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.        NARRI:  2(5+9+0) x (2+0) = 56  Cause Code = 418

column168: DRIVER ON H-1 FREEWAY LEFT LANE BEFORE KUNIA EXIT WHEN HE HEARD A LOUD SOUND AND FELT SOMETHING UNDER HIS TRUCK.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER INTO THE MEDIAN AND JUMPED OUT FROM THE CAB TO LOOK UNDER THE TRUCK.  HE SAW GASOLINE FLOWING FROM THE FIRST COMPARTMENT OF THE TRUCK AND THE DRIVE SHAFT AND PARTS OF THE DRIVE SHAFT ON THE ROAD.    DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED 911 AND ASKED FOR FIRE DEPARTMENT TO BE DISPATCHED TO HIS LOCATION BECAUSE OF GASOLINE LEAKING OUT OF HIS TRUCK COMPARTMENT.  POLICE WERE ALSO DISPATCHED.  FIRE AND POLICE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND CLOSED OFF  H-1 FREEWAY WEST BOUND AND H-1 FREEWAY EASTBOUND AT MAKAKILO EXIT.  HFD COMMAND POST SET UP WAS UPWIND OF SPILL SITE.  DRIVER ALSO CALL ALOHA PETROLEUM DISPATCH, TRUCKING SUPERVISOR DIANA PUULEI AND SHE CALLED FUEL DISTRIBUTION MANAGER PATRICK IONA. HES MANAGER, JANE MACKEE WAS DRIVING DOWN THE FREEWAY WHEN THIS OCCURRED AND PULLED OVER TO HELP DRIVER AND WORK WITH HONOLULU FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS UNTIL THE REST OF ALOHA'S RESPONSE TEAM COULD ASSEMBLE.  DIANA PUULEI CALL DARRELL BUSSELL AT PHILIPS SERVICES TO COORDINATE PUMPING OUT THE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TRUCK TANK #1 (2500 GALLONS); AND TRUCK TANK #2 (2000 GALLONS).  ALOHA DISPATCH CONTACTED AFFORDABLE TOWING TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL SITE; HES MANAGER JANE MCKEE CALLED IN ENVIRONMENT CONSULTANT NED PURPHY TO TAKE SOIL SAMPLES AND DELENIATE THE SPILL SITE.    PATRICK IONA WORKED WITH ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF ROLAND HARVEST AT THE COMMAND SITE WITH HIS HASMAT AND RESPONSE CAPTAINS ON THE BEST WAY TO PUMPOUT THE TRUCK TANKS. A FOAM BLANKET WAS SPRAYED TO KEEP THE GASOLINE VAPORS DOWN.  IT WAS AGREED THAT ONCE THE VACUMN TRUCK HAD ARRIVED, THE FOAM BLANKET WOULD BE LAID AGAIN AND THE HAZMAT TEAM WOULD HOOKUP THE 3"INCH HOSES TO THE DISCHARGE VALVES ON THE 1ST COMPARTMENT.  ONCE COMPLETED WE WOULD THEN PUMP OUT THE 2ND COMPARTMENT OF 2,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. FOLLOWING THE REMOVAL OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRUCK, THE TOW TRUCK WOULD THEN HOOKUP A CABLE TO THE TRUCK AND PULL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OUT FROM THE SPILLED AREA BACK ONTO THE FREEWAY, COMPLETE HOOKUPS AND TOW THE TRUCK AND TRAILER BACK TO ALOHA PETROLEUM'S TERMINAL YARD AT 91-119 HANUA STREET.  A POLICE AND FIRE TRUCK ESCORT WOULD ACCOMPANY THE TOW TRUCK.  BY THE TIME THIS WAS COMPLETED PATRICK IONA HAD PHILIP SERVICES HAWAII MANAGER DARRELL BUSSELL CONTACT EXCAVATOR COMPANY TAGAMI CONSTRUCTION TO BRING IN AN EXCAVATOR, ROLLOFFS HAWAII TO BRING IN ROLLOFF CONTAINERS FOR THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, B&C TRUCKING TO BRING IN NEW CLEAN SOIL, A BACKHOE UNIT, SAFETY SYSTEM SUPPLIES TO BRING IN A FREEWAY DIRECTIONAL ARROW, ORANGE FREEWAY CONES AND ANOTHER 70 BBL. VACUMN TRUCK TO STANDBY TO SUCKUP ANY LIQUID PRODUCT WHILE EXCAVATING THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  STATE OF HAWAII HAZARD EVALUATION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGER TERRY CORPUZ WAS ON SITE AND WE CONSULTED WITH HIM AT THE COMMAND POST.  WE EXPLAINED TO TERRY CORPUZ THAT WE WOULD DELINEATE THE SPILL SITE ONCE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE
column169: THE FAILUREOF THE DRIVESHAFT IS NOT SOMETHING YOU CAN FORESEE.  WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED A SERVICE CHECK EACH MONTH OF THE ALOHA TRUCK FLEET'S DRIVESHAFTS TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE ALL GREASED, AND ALL BOLTS ARE TIGHT.

column168: On February 2 when the leak was discovered by the car inspector inspecting the train, the car was isolated and employees told to stay away from car.  Eagle Construction out of Findlay, Ohio was called inmmediately to respond and assess the problem.  When they looked over the situation, they said that the packing on the liquid unloading line needed tightened but the nut on the valve stem was stripped and it could not be tightened.  The shipper was contacted and they wanted a contractor of their choice to look at the car and see if it could be repaired.  Their contractor, ResCarr responded on the follwing Tuesday the 10th.  They said that the valve would need replaced.  They ordered a new valve and they came back out on the 12th to replace it. A movement approval was sought by the railroad to get the car to destination where it was unloaded. The approval was recieved on Feb 13th.  The car moved that day and was delivered to the consignee on Feb 15th. The consignee received a movement approval for its movement back to Sarnia, Ontario.  The car was tagged as not to load per movement approval instructions.  The car needed movement approval becasue even though a new valve stopped the leak, a leak proffness test could not be performed in the field and it needed sent to home shop for the test.

column168: While working in the Beaumont, Texas rail yard, KCS employee Kenneth Setliff received an acid splash from UTLX 11697 moving in adjacent track. column168: On 2/18/09, one of our customers reported that we had shipped them an undeclared substance that should have been declared as hazardous.  After reviewing the allegation, we discovered there had been a data entry error made within our operating system in November of 2006.  This error caused the material to be classified as non-hazardous when in fact it should have been classified as UN1866 PGIII.  Subsequently, we have made multiple shipments with this incorrect classification.  The dates and number of containers are listed below:   Date    Quantity      4-27-07 2  5-15-07 2  7-17-07 2  8-6-07 2  8-13-07 2  9-12-07 2  12-7-07 2  1-3-08 2  2-22-08 2  4-18-08 2  5-16-08 2  6-15-08 2  6-26-08 2  7-2-08 2  7-21-08 4  8-5-08 2  9-2-08 2  10-3-08 2  11-7-08 2  12-01-08 2  2-5-09 4
column169: The following actions will be taken to prevent recurrence: As of 2/19/09, the procedure pertaining to the system maintenance that caused this error has been reviewed.  We will have documented training on the procedure pertaining to the system maintenance that caused this error.  We will review all data of this type created since November 2006 and verify its dangerous goods classification.  When complete, the review will be documented.

column168: A van trailer was transporting 6 1/2 inch diameter by 30 inch long plastic bags of blasting agent. There were a total of 1,125 bags with a net weight of 45,000 pounds.  Each bag weighed 40 pounds.  A tire blew on the rear of the trailer at mile marker 4 on I-75/24 in Chattanooga, TN,  The blown tire caused a tear in the van trailer which allowed 20 bags to fall out of the trailer.  The driver could not stop immediatley because the guard rail was too close to the road.  After approximately one mile the driver pulled to the shoulder.  As a result, 20 bags were ruptured and spilled along side the road.
column169: Although this incident could have possibly been the result of a tire failure or a road hazard, Nelson Brothers, LLC will re-train drivers in pre-trip inspections.

column168: The shipment arrived ABQ at approximately 0930 on February 20, 2009.  The packages were placed in a storage cart outside the cargo facility within a SIDA security area.  At approximately 1530 the PM Cargo agent, Joseph Davis, completed a sweep of the facility for any remaining cargo that needed checked in.  He observed one of the 12 packages was leaking a silver liquid substance.  He immediately notified local management, contacted the airport emergency response line and secured the area.  Emergency response advised there was no action for them to take since the spill was contained and immediate area evacuated.  Shipper and consignee were contacted and advised of situation.  Consignee, Schott Solar Inc. (Rinchem), dispatched a cleanup team to manage the spill.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was unloading regular unleaded gasoline to a customer location. While unloading driver noticed fuel beginning to leak out of the vapor recover line of tank number 2. Driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 10 gallons spilled into the concrete containment area. Product was completely cleaned by driver and FRTL management. Chattahoochee Environmental repsonded to scene and confirmed that no product reached soil or drains and product was cleaned properly. Upon investigation it was determined that the driver failed to calculate tank compacity properly and was not using tank charts but rather relied on the store's electronic tank gauging system, which calculates capacity at 100% of tank size as opposed to FRTL's company policy of 90% safe fill capacity.
column169: The driver failed to follow proper unloading procedures. Upon returning to work an Incident Prevention Observation will be conducted on the driver while unloading as well as a requirement to attend a refresher training class given by a Regional Safety Supervisor.

column168: On 2/4 a fibreboard box with no Hazmat markings was loaded on Republic Airlines Flight # 2425 from MKE (Milwaukee) to MCI (Kansas City).  The box contained 12 cans of 13oz each of 'Lysol Neutra Air'.  The box was packed, shipped and loaded by Midwest Airlines employees as part of a COMAT (Company Materials) shipment from the Milwaukee (MKE) station to the Kansas City (MCI) station.    Republic Airlines is the aircraft operator under contract by MIdwest Airlines.    Upon arrival at MCI, the box was unloaded and transported to the cargo facility by Midwest employees where upon opening it was discovered to be an undeclared hazmat shipment.  Subsequent verification of the MSDS showed them to be classified as "UN1950, Aerosols, Flammable".      Midwest Airlines reported the incident internally via their 'Occurrence Investigation Report" on February 5, 2009, and notified Republic Airlines, the aircraft operator, on february 11, 2009.    The incident is being investigated by Republic Airlines, Midwest Airlines and the FAA.
column169: The incident is still under investigation.  Focus is on contractor training, following of established procedures and a comprehensive review of the hazmat training program.

The car was sent to a tank car shop for further inspection and repairs to the defective valve under FRA Movement Authority.

column168: Driver completed loading the trailer and left the shipper and drove approximately 6 miles.  Arrived at the Highway 30 Truck Stop and fueled.  Traveled another 5 miles.  When the driver was slowing his vehicle for a traffic light, he noticed product leaking from the top of the trailer.  Upon inspection he noticed that the front washout cap was missing.  Driver stated that threads were intact and in good condition.  Driver replaced washout cap and continued his trip.
column169: Driver was issued a corrective action letter and has competed company required remedial training governing Tanker Pre-Trip Inspections.  To help prevent future occurances, the local terminal's shop mechanics will begin checking the washout caps and sealing them prior to being assigned to a driver.  This will add another check to ensure that these washout caps are in place and secured after the trailer is prepared for loading at a shipper.

column168: Driver uses his tractor mounted product pump and hoses to make delivery.  Product was at normal temprature and viscosity and there were no unsual sercumstances  present at the time. Driver said he was pumping with normal pressure using 3 inch  suction and 2 inch discharg chemical hose. said thea after about five minutes of product transfer the discharge hose ruptured at about 18 inches from the hose end that was connected to the pump. Driver was in attendance and shut down the pump.  The spilled material was contained and cleaned up by driver and plant operator.  Driver replaced the damaged hose and compleated delivery without further incident.
column169: The damaged hose was cleaned and removed from service and will be inspected.  The carrier has an active hose testing policy in place which calls for chemical product transfer hoses to be inspected and pressure tested every other quarter.  Also, the drivers are to inspect hoses prior to every use.  When interviewed, the driver said he did not see any visible signs of damage to the hose prior to its failure. This incident is still under investigation.

column168: Material handler was unloading freight from trailer he was assigned to unload. When he unloaded this box he placed it on top of the forklift since it was so small and picked up a staged pallet with the forklift that he was operating. As he was backing out of the trailer the box that was on top of the forklift fell off into the path of the forklift and as a result was crushed contributing to the unintentional release.
column169: Material handlers should not use the top of the forklift to transport freight with. Must use equipment the way it was intended and designed to operate.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver delivering gasoline, conducted a before stick reading, he failed to accurately read the stick reading and believed he had enough capacity to deliver the product into the 20,000 gallon underground storage tank.  In reality he did not. He began to drop and also failed to cap the second drop tube.  In so doing when he overfilled the tank product came up through the uncapped drop tube resulting in a seven gallon spill onto the pavement and in the spill containment bucket.  The driver immediately closed the internal valved for the trailer compartment, to stop the flow of product.  He then utilzed the spill kit on the tanker and the spill response supplies at the store to contain and clean up the seven gallon spill.
column169: After a debriefing of the incident, the driver realizes that he made two errors, one he did not accurately read the before stick reading and two he did not put the cap on the second drop tube.  Both errors have been identified and addressed. They are a required part of our standard delivery procedures, which the driver is aware of and this has been discussed again with him.

column168: On February 13th at 18:47 hours, personnel in the CSXT Florence Yard, in Florence, SC discovered GATX 66285, a loaded tank car of Alkylphenols, Solid, N.O.S. leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was isolated and the shipper, Albemarle Corporation was notified via Chemtrec (Report Number 2009021300189).  Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the tank car was leaking between the bottom outlet valve connection and the tank body.  Hepaco was able to slow the product leak to four (4) ounces every forty-eight (48) hours.  The shipper submitted a request for FRA Movement approval and was granted authorization (FRA-09020067).  The information was added to the waybill and the car was forwarded back to Albermarle Corporation in Orangeburg, South Carolina.  Approximately one gallon of product was released.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move to the car repair shop track.          NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100  Cause Code = 544
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During the unloading process, a small puddle was forming on the ground, at the connection site.  Upon investigation, it was discovered that the gasket on the hose was causing the leak.
column169: The driver did what was expected.  He checked his valves and connections to correct the problem.  It was discovered that it was the unloader's hose and gasket that was causing the leak.  Being that the unloading at this particular Customer is their responsibility, our driver did what he could to prevent this occurrence from happening.

column168: On 02/20/2009 at 19:34 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Moncrief Yard, Jacksonville, FL  discovered ACFX 94836, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Alcohol, leaking from bottom outlet. The car was isolated and CHEMTREC (Report #2009022000167) was notified but the shipper was not listed with CHEMTREC. The shipper was notified by the CSXT Hazardous Materials manager on call and notified of the incident. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet cap was not attached and the bottom outlet valve was dripping product. SWS personnel installed a cap gasket, installed the bottom outlet cap wrench tight and cleaned up the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. An AAR 7.1 QA program nonconformance report was not performed.     NARRI:  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause code = 569
column169: No additional comments.

column168: GATX 3886 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported with a product odor and vapor release emanating from around the manway area atop this tank car. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 3886 and later reported that the manway gasket was out of position and an eight inch portion of this gasket was crimped. GATX 3886 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting corrective action from the nearby shipper. The shipper responder scrubbed alkaline vapors and renewed the manway gasket by 1615 hrs. PST, 2/28/09. No liquid product release was associated with this incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver heading East on Colorado State Hwy 36 (2-lane) - Tractor/Trailer rig - Driver stated that he exited the roadway to the right (south) into a grain storage facility lot due to an oversize load approaching. He entered the lot making a turn around, approached the entrance to pull back out onto the highway, began to pull back out when the rear escort vehicle for the oversize load approached him coming from around a blind curve a short distance to the East of where he was pulling out. Driver tried to cut back dropping the passenger-side trailer tires into culvert putting trailer on it's side. The Colorado State Patrol, a wrecker service, a response team, another tanker and a vacuum truck were called. They off-loaded the tanker onto the other tanker, the vacuum truck sucked up as much liquid as possible, and the response team excavated the contaminated dirt and replaced it with clean dirt according to C-DOT specifications and approval. When the truck went onto it's side, the vapor recovery valve had something stuck in it keeping it in the open position.
column169: Review safe driving and safety inspection procedures with all employees.

column168: On February 10, 2009 at approximately 16:30 hours, personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay Yard were notified by FRA Inspector Matsinger that she discovered NATX 300668, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S leaking from the bottom outlet. The car was inspected by a CSXT Sentinel who reported the bottom outlet cap was tool tight and the valve handle was in the closed locked position. It was reported that there was only wetness around the bottom outlet cap. FRA Inspector Matsinger and the FRA DC office authorized the car to be moved one mile to the Atlantic Terminal to be off loaded. The shipper, Poet Ethanol Products, was notified that the car would need to go to a home shop for repairs.  The car was off loaded and SPSI, an emergency response contractor, was contacted to clean and purge the car. The car was sent to BRC Rail Car Services in Lynchburg, VA., to be repaired.    Cause Code:  551  NARRI:  2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32
column169: No additional comments.

The 3 loose plugs were made tool tight stopping the release.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UTLX 11071 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) with a small vapor expulsion from the top fitting area during normal switching activity in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 11071 was cordoned off in the railyard. Nearby BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 11071 finding the vapor line's four blind flange bolts finger loose. The responders tool tightened these loose bolts. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. A very small amount of wetness from the vapor release on the top tank shell was diluted with water. Response was concluded by 2320 hrs. CST, 2/17/09. No ground impact from this vapor release was evident.

column168: During deramping of intermodal trailer FSTZ 884585 from its inbound rail intermodal flatcar, ramp employees reported that this trailer had leaked an unknown substance atop the platform of the flatcar. Once grounded, FSTZ 884585 was directed to the containment area for follow-up inspection. BNSF contract responders cleaned the spillage atop the rail flatcar with absorbent material followed by an application of a microbial bioremediation agent. The responders then inspected FSTZ 884585. One steel 55 gallon drum was found toward the trailer's nose that had leaked from a cut in this drum's sidewall. The responder's assessment was that the cut appeared to be from a forklift tine and most likely damaged during drum loading into the trailer. The cut in the drum was sealed with putty and then placed into an overpack/recovery drum for future appropriate disposal. The spillage atop the trailer floor was absorbed and cleaned. Afterwards, all drums removed were repositioned inside FSTZ 884585 properly blocked and braced for continued transportation. All absorbent and cleaning materials were placed inside a sealable container for appropriate disposal.

Indiana State Police responded to accident minutes later, driver was extracted from vehicle and taken to hospital.  Spill Recovery of Indiana were on the scene in less than 30 minutes.  Trailer was loaded with 8502 gallons of gasoline, and was leaking gas from the front right side of tanker.  A baseball size hole was caused by the damage to the trailer.  A wooden stake was placed in the whole to stop leakage.  Only 444 gallons were unrecovered.  The product left remaining on the tanker was pumped out and delivered to our facility.  Absorbant booms and pads were placed all around the unit  by Spill Recovery of Indiana immediatley upon their arrival.  Site was excavated by Summit Environmental and all contaminated soil was disposed of.  New Soil and grass has been planted.  All work is complete at site.

column168: Employee was traveling West bound when the left rear tire apparently came off resulting in the driver loosing control of the truck. This was confirmed / cleared by Hazmat.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years

column168: UNKOWN CAUSE OF PACKAGE FAILURE. WAS DISCOVERED IN THE BELLY OF AMERIFLIGHT # 1900 AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 BY 2 UNLOADERS (EVERGREEN RAMP AGENTS). column168: AT 20:00 A CALL WAS SENT FROM DAMIAN A SUPERVISOR ON A2 REPORTING A WET PACKAGE AND NEEDED A DESIGNATED RESPONDER TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE. column168: 0510- Driver was traveling westbound on GA Route 156. He stated that several deer ran into his lane causing him to take evasive action. Tanker piping and 2" valve on top of tanker sheared off after impact with the ground causing the leak.   Lt ZW Gilbert with the Gordon Co Fire Dept took charge of hte scene.  Marion Environmental Co was assigned for clean up and disposal of waste material.  Both GA State Patrop and GA Public Safety were on the scene along with GA EPD and the GA Hazmat Team.

column169: ISSUED A WARNING LETTER AND APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE, WITH REVIEWS AND INSTRUCTIONS ON SAFE PROCEDURES REGARDING PROPER UNLOADING, LOADING AND HANDLING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FREIGHT.  RETRAINING SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUID OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGE IT.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING INHAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LAY AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: Driver had completed the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He had disconnected the transfer hoses and drained them in a bucket.  A gust of wind blew the bucket over.  Most of the product went on spill pad under the bucket but some went in the containment area.  It was cleaned up by the customer.
column169: Gusts of wind are unpredictable.  If the driver knew it was windy, he should have made sure the bucket was in a secure location.

column168: The driver was using air pressure to transfer 1504 gallons of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  The storage tank had a capacity of 3500 gallons and it had 300 gallons in it to start.  At the end of the unload, driver noticed foam coming out of the vent on the customer storage tank.   The foam/spill went into an open grate under the tank with a holding pit.  Customer said that usually the bill of lading instructions say to use pump only because product foams easily.  It was not printed on this BOL.
column169: Customer will see that "pump only" is written on the BOL in the future.  I also added that note to the commodity information that we send to the driver.

column168: During the midnight sort operations at the UPS building in Forest Park, GA, an employee noticed flames coming from a package as it proceeded up a conveyor belt from the primary sort. Two employees extinguished the package with fire extinguishers, while the workforce was evacuated. The fire department arrived after the fire was out. After the fire was extinguished, the remnants of the outer package and its six aerosol cans were collected for post-incident inspection. One can was found to be empty and there was a puncture near the bottom rim of the can. All address information and part of the package specification marking were destroyed by the fire.
column169: The incident was reported to the local PHMSA office to draw attention to the continuation of a pattern observed in UPS operations. This is the fourth aerosol fire in less than 12 months in which a can released its contents through a puncture just above the bottom rim, It is recommended that packaging requirements for aerosols be evaluated to reduce the opportunity for can-to-can contact within a package.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: 05:35 - Driver was making a left hand turn from Charleston Blvd. onto Lamb Blvd. northbound in North Las Vegas,NV.  Driver took the turn at 15 miles per hour. The truck was top heavy, resulting in the vehicle tipping over onto its side; causing the hydraulic lock lid to bend, releasing approximately 4,000-5,000lbs of Ammonium Nitrate, and less than 1 gallon of fuel/hydraulic oil onto the sidewalk of Lamb Blvd.  The fuel/hydraulic oil was kept separate from the Ammonium Nitrate by the vehicle operator.  Driver immediately called supervisor, the sheriff's department and the fire department who, in turn, called Chemtrec: our hazardous materials emergency response team.  Chemtrec then made a series of phone calls to emergency response units and Sanders Construction, Inc. management.  Fire department unnecessarily evacuated the area within 1,000' of the spill.  Sanders Construction, Inc. supervisory and cleanup detail were on site within 45 minutes of the spill at which time the spill site was immediately declared non-life threatening.  Cleanup procedure commenced immediately after the vehicle was placed upright.  No leakage of Ammonium Nitrate or fuel was able to enter into the public water system including drains and gutters. 100% of Ammonium Nitrate was reclaimed.  Cleanup lasted approximately 4 - 5 hours, after which traffic resumed.
column169: Driver was severely reprimanded.  He has also been required to be trained again in all things regarding the loading and unloading of hazardous materials and oversized loads.

column169: FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURE IN CONTAINING A LEAK AT YOUR FACILITY. PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO BE EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: The driver arrived at Speedway in South Point, OH to deliver Kerosene.  He hooked his hose and fitting to the drop piping and began to unload the product. The driver was alerted by the store attendant that product was running out on the ground.  The driver shut down operation and helped spread absorbent and spill pads.  The driver dribbled the remaining product into the tank, shut down and helped clean up the area.  An environmental company was called into further clean up the area and remove product from the storm drain.  When they arrived they flushed and vacuumed the storm drain, cleaned the apron around the drop site and disposed of the materials.  Approximately 100 gallons overflowed from the spill containment bucket.  It was discovered that the plunger in the bottom of the spill containment bucket had been removed and plugged.  The plug blew out due to a vent restriction in the underground storage tank.
column169: We are going to discuss, train and improve our unloading procedures by helping drivers identify possible problems with underground storage tanks (spill containment equipment and safety features, vent piping at service stations.)

Our driver was awakened while parked at the Flying J Travel Plaza.  He was informed that his trailer was on fire.  Upon inspection, it was noted that the trailer door was ajar, his padlock had been broken and was lying on the ground behind the trailer, and a pair of bolt cutters was found next to the trailer.    In an effort to mitigate the effects, our driver then drove the truck away from the travel plaza to a farm road near the travel plaza.  Emergency responders were on the scene quickly to control the situation.    The Ripon Police Department was handling this as an arson case.
column169: As the circumstances are of suspicious nature, a better course of action could not be determined.  Our driver used his best judgement to move the burning trailer out of harm's way, thereby preventing serious damage to the travel plaza and other vehicles.

column168: AT 1720 HRS. ON FEBRUARY 15, 2009 A SWITCHING CREW SAW A LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RTMX 13086 IN COTTON WAREHOUSE YEARD.  THEY NOTIFIED THE YARDMASTER AND THE YARD WAS SHUT DOWN.  THE STATE POLICE WERE NOTIFIED ALONG WITH THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPT., NEW ORLEANS POLICE AND HARBOR POLICE.  I WAS NOTIFIED, AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  I LET THEM KNOW THE CAR WAS LEAKING TERPENE HYDROCARBONS UN 2319, A CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THEY ARRIVED AT 1840 HRS. AND DETERMINED THE CAR WAS LEAKING AROUND THE MANWAY COVER.  UPON REMOVING THE LID TWO GASKETS WERE FOUND, BOTH WERE IN TERRIBLE CONDITION.  THEY WERE REMOVED AND REPLACED BY A NEW RIM NOZZLE GASKET.  A NEW SEAL WAS INSTALLED, AND THE CAR WAS SPRAYED WITH ADETERGENT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE RAILROAD FOR TRANSPORT.  THE COTTON WAREHOUSE YARD WAS RE-OPENED.  THE STATE POLICE WAS CONTACTED AND THE INCIDENT WAS CLOSED AT 1945 HRS.

column168: On February, 24, 2009, at 10:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate yard, discovered GATX 71755, a loaded tank car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine, leaking from the top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper and local Fire Department were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2009-02-24-00064). A CSXT Sentinel located the source of the leak from around the top operated bottom opening valve.  Upon investigation, the CSXT Sentinel noted the absence of packing material behind the packing gland nut.  The CSXT Sentinel removed the retaining nut, applied a Teflon gasket rope and resecured the retaining nut.  The leak stopped and the car was released for transport. A CSXT emergency response contractor decontaminated the car. This incident did require a special switching move.      An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.    Cause Code: 534  NARRI: 5 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60

column169: WE MUST SECURE ALL SHIPMENTS WHEN LOADING. PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOAD! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: ON FEB. 24TH, I WAS DELIVERING RED DYED DIESEL TO A NEW ACCOUNT.  (MARK WEBBER) THERE WERE TWO OVERHEAD 500 GALLON TANKS THAT NEEDED TO BE FILLED.  ONE WAS IN A CONTAINMENT AND THE OTHER WAS FREE STANDING.  I FILLED THE FREE STANDING TANK FIRST AND THEN STARTED TO FILL THE TANK THAT WAS IN THE CONTAINMENT.  THE STAND ON THE FREE THEN SUNK INTO THE MUD AND THE TANK FELL OFF THE STAND UPSIDE DOWN AND BEGAN TO SPILL.  WITH A SHOVEL I WAS ABLE TO DIVERT THE FUEL ACROSS THE DRIVEWAY AND AWAY FROM DRAINAGE CULVERTS UNDER COUNTY ROAD 318.  I ESTIMATED ABOUT 300 GALLONS SPILLED FROM THE TANK.  THE FUEL SETTLED IN A LOW SPOT IN A FIELD.  I THEN CALLED THE PERS HOTLINE.  A COWORKER CALLED CUMMINS BURNER FUEL TO COME AND SUCK UP THE FUEL THAT HAD SETTLED IN THE FIELD.  WE USED SPILL PADS TO SOAK UP ALL OTHER SMALL POOLS THAT HAD FORMED.

column168: The incident in this case was receipt of an undeclared hazardous material shipment from Elantas, PDG to Siemens Energy, Inc. There was no release of hazardous material. The initial cause of attention was an odor of styrene in thetrailer, however, it was determined that this was due to the container cap which is designed to vent pressure. Since this material was known to be a Class 3 flammable liquid, it was then noted that there were no "flammable" lables on the 4 containers, and no palcards on the truck. Examination of the shipping papers showed that the materials had been described as "TOTE(S) NOT REGULATED UNDER CFR 49". The 4 totes were unloaded and "flammable"labels affixed ot them. The shipper was notified immediately that the undeclared shipment had been received at Fort Payne, and that an incident report would be filed with the Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration of USDOT. The shipper, after conducting an internal investigation, reported that as a result of a clerical error in entering material into their accounting system, the wrong material code was assigned to the shipment, and labels printed for the shipment were actually for another material that was not hazardous. They also reported that the error had been corrected, and that they expected no similar occurences in the future.
column169: We believe it was recent hazardous materials training that resulted in heightened awareness on the part of personnel unloading the truck, and triggered the reporting of the incident. We have determined to include audits of receiving records in our internal auditing program, and have encouraged the shipper to do so with their shipping records.

column168: The shipment was picked up by the carrier and transfered to the next terminal to be loaded to the destination. U/A the bags were noticed leaking small amounts from multiple skids and packages. Further investigation revealed the weight of the bags on each skid had caused the boards on the skids to bowe and the nails in the skid to pop causing small holes in the bags against the skid surface. There was not a barrier (paper or cardboard) betweeen the skid surface and the bagged product. The carrier notified the shipper who originally had the material described as Disodium salt, anhydrous, 8, UN3253, PGII. Research of the product revealed this to be an incorrect descrpition as the UN3253 is not available in PGII nor was the shipping name represented on the bill of lading associated with the UNID provided by the shipper. Numerous attempts to obtain the correct description as stated on the manufacturers MSDS went unanswered. After nearly 8 weeks of notification to the shipper of the defficiency and requests for disposition for the released product the shipper sent the updated shipping name and UN to reflect the MSDS supplied by the shipper on April 16, 2009. The correct UNID and shipping name are used in this report. The shipment was ultimately authorized by the shipper to be repackaged and returned. U/a arrival to the carriers terminal for the return process the bags which had not leaked during the first phase of transportation released product again for the same reason stated above. The shipper ultimately authorized the delivery of the recouped product which was not returned to the shipper and held at the carriers facility to be overpacked and moved to the consignee. The release was managed in 2 hours. The time frame to manage the shipment was nearly 8 weeks due to lack of cooperation from the shipper tendering the product to the carrier. No exposures or injuries resulted from this incident.
column169: Use of hard wood skids and a protective barrier would have certainly prevented this occurrence. The lack of cooperation from the shipper and the obvious lack of training played a definite roll in the lenght of time it took to mediate the release and get the necessary corrections required for the paperwork.

column168: This is a report of the tank car GATX 56935 derailment incident of February 3, 2009. Conrail brought the car in question to our facility on the afternoon of February 3. There had been a heavy snow in the area and the tracks were partially covered in snow. Our maintenance personnel went to move the car into our tank car barn per normal procedure using our Trackmaster. As the car moved past the last switch before going into the barn, the back wheels of the tank car went off the track, also derailing the Trackmaster. Several attempts were made to get the tank car and the Trackmaster back on the track. At the end of the day our maintenance staff was able to get the Trackmaster out but the tank car as still derailed. Calls were made to Conrail for assistance and they told our staff that they would come in the morning to move the car back on the track.  Conrail personnel arrived the next morning with equipment and were able to get the tank car back on the track. We moved the car into the barn where it was found that the back wheels suffered damage. The tank, however, was not damaged and we were able to feed product into our facility with no problem. We contacted the vendor and informed them of the incident. The vendor was able to get in contact with the owner of the tank car, GATX, who is advising them on who to get to fix the car.  At this time, the car is offloading product and should be empty by March 27. In our investigation of the incident, we found that ice got into the switch. The ice did not allow the switch to function as designed and this caused the derailment. In the future, we will make sure that the tracks are cleared and that the switches are properly de-iced so that they can function properly.

column169: BETTER HANDLING OF OUTBOUND TRANSFER OF HAZARDOUS AND POTENTIALLY HAZARDOUS SHIPMENTS. USE PROPER LOAD TECHNIQUES. USE BLOCKING AND BRACING. PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS,PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON HWY 39 (SOUTH) AND THE ROADWAY WAS ICE COVERED.  THE UNIT VEERED LEFT ACROSS ON COMING LANE, OFF ROADWAY ALONG A 3-4 FOOT ENBANKMENT (ACCORDING TO TIRE MARKS).  THE EVENTUALLY FLIP OVER AND CAME TO REST ABOUT 30 YEARS OF THE ROADWAY.  THE TANKER HAD 2 COMPARTMENTS OF GASOLINE, 2 COMPARTMENTS OF DIESEL FUEL & 1 COMPARTMENT WAS EMPTY.  THE INTEGRITY OF THE INTERNAL COMPARTMENTS FAILED ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO MIX INSIDE THE TANKER THE FIRE VALVE HANDLES WERE TORN OFF AND PRODUCT BEGAIN LEAKING INTO DAMAGE PIPING UNDER TANKER AND ONTO THE GROUND AROUND THE UNIT.  THE FIRE DEPARMENT ARRIVED AND CLOSED THE EMERGENCY VALVES STOPPING THE RELEASE.

column168: DRIVER WAS EAST BOUND ON I-94 NEAR LA PORTE, IN.  ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 02:25AM IN THE MORNING.  IT WAS DARK WITH NO STREET LIGHTS, WEATHER WAS COLD BUT CLEAR, NOT RAINING OR FOGGY AND PAVEMENT DRY.  DRIVER STATES THAT A TRACTOR AND TRAILER RIG WAS PASSING ON HIS LEFT AND SWERVED TO THE RIGHT FORCING HIM TO SERVE TO THE RIGHT; HE LOST CONTROL AND THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER INTO THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A SECOND VEHICLE BEING INVOLVED.  NO OTHER WITNESS AND THE DAMAGE TO THE VEHICLE DID NOT INDICATE CONTACT WAS MADE WITH ANY OTHER VEHICLE.  WE ARE NOT SAYING THERE WAS NOT ANOTHER VEHICLE, JUST THAT THERE IS NO EVIDENCE THAT SHOWS A SECOND VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED.  THE CARGO TANK MAINTAINED ITS STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY AND DID NOT RELEASE ANY PRODUCT/CARGO.  THE CARGO TANK WAS PUMPED OUT AT THE SCENE INTO ANOTHER VEHICLE WITHOUT ANY LOSS OF CARGO.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTY (50) GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL LEAKED OUT OF THE TRACTOR'S FUEL TANKS WHICH REQUIRED CLEAN UP.  THE MAJORITY OF THE ACCIDENT RECOVERY COST WAS FOR EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL TO SAFELY TRANSFER THE CARGO FROM THE OVERTURNED TRAILER AND STORAGE AND COMPLETING THE DELIVERY OF THE CARGO.  THE COST OF THE CLEAN UP OF THE DIESEL FUEL WAS INCLUDED IN THE ACCIDENT RECOVERY COST.  THE TRACTOR WAS DEEMED A TOTAL LOSS BY THE INSURANCE COMPANY AND OWNER OF THE VEHICLE.  THE DOT 407 CARGO TANK RECEIVED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE.  THE TANK WAS DISTORTED WITH A SLIGHT TWIST AND THE FRONT BULKHEAD RECEIVED CONSIDERABLE DAMAGE.  THE TRAILER WAS CONSIDERED DAMAGED BEYOND ECONOMICAL REPAIR AND WAS DISPOSED OF.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 19, 2009 AT 1:30PM, EDWARD KURTH WAS AT BJ SERVICES YARD TO UNLOAD HIS LOAD OF DIESEL.  HE HOOKED UP ALL OF HIS HOSES TO THEIR TANK BUT ONE OF THE EARS WAS NOT FIRMLY SECURED WHEN HE BEGAN PUMPING THE FUEL.  WHEN THE PUMP PRESSURED UP AND SENT FUEL THROUGH THE LINE, THE HOOKUP CAME LOOSE AND BEGAN PUMPING FUEL OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  BY THE TIME THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT OFF THE PUMP, HE HAD ALREADY PUMPUED OUT 300-500 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO THE GROUND.  WORKERS AT BJ'S WERE ON HAND VERY QUICKLY WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS TOHOLD THE FUEL IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  I WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO SEE WHAT HAD HAPPENED.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND THEY WERE ON THE SCENE WITHIN 2 HOURS.  THEY COVERED THE AREA IN CASE OF RAIN AND RETURNED AFTER ALL POWER, GAS, AND WATER LINES HAD BEEN MARKED.  THEY DUG UP ALL OF THE AFFECTED SOIL AND GRAVEL AND TESTED THE GROUND TO MAKE SURE THEY GOT ALL MATERIALS THAT WERE AFFECTED.  THEY THEN BROUGHT IN NEW GRAVEL TO REPLACE ALL THE GRAVEL THAT WAS TAKEN OUT.
column169: REVIEW WITH DRIVERS THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE THE LOCK DOWN EARS ON THE TIGHT FITS & HOSES ARE PROPERLY SECURED BEFORE DRIVER BEGINS PUMPING OR UNLOADING FUEL.

column168: OUR EMPLOYEE WAS BRING A 1000 GAL PORTABLE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TRAILER AT APPROXIMATELY 25 MPH, ON A DIRT ROAD IN RURAL SCOTT COUNTY, KS.  A PIN THAT HOLDS THE HITCH FRAME TO THE FRAME AT THE PICKUP BROKE CAUSING THE TRAILER TO COME LLOSE FROM THE PICKUP (OTHER THAN THE SAFETY CHAINS). THE TRAILER WHIPPED BACK AND FORTH AND THEN ROLLED OVER BREAKING THE VAPORT RELIEF VALVE ON THE TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 2800 LBS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  ONCE PRODUCT HAD BLED OFF BELOW THE LEVEL OF THE VALVE, THE TANK QUIT LEAKING.  LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THEY SECURED THE SCENE, UNTIL THE TANK QUIT LEAKING, AND THE TANK WAS ROLLED BACK OVER AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR FACILITY.
column169: PRIOR TO TOWING AMMONIA USED TRAILERS WE ARE REQUIRING OUR EMPLOYEES TO INSPECT ALL HITCHES ON TOWING VEHICLES FOR WEAR AND EQUIPMENT FATIGUE, AND TO MAKE THOSE REPAIRS WHEN NECESSARY PRIOR TO TOWING ALL TANKS OF THIS CLASSIFICATION.

column168: ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TRAILER (TANK #6) WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO FARMER'S FIELD BEHIND A PICKUP TRUCK.  THE NURSE TANK WHIPPED TO THE SIDE AND BROKE LOOSE FROM THE PICKUP TRUCK.  THE TANK OVERTURNED, LOOSENING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  APPROXIMATELY, 16 GALLONS OR 89 LBS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WERE RELEASED OVER A 15 TO 20 MINUTE PERIOD.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM MOBILIZED ON SCENE TO APPLY WATER TO DISPERSE THE AMMONIA CLOUD SO THE VALVE COULD BE TIGHTENED.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE NURSE TANK TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE LOCAL FACILITY WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK.  TANK #6 WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AFTER THIS INCIDENT.
